{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411386"},"attributes":{"position":7,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17474010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17474010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:17:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11692"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11692"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.34,0.42,0.14,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109866"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4307"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92235"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1058"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109866"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department. Whilst at a family gathering, she experienced sudden onset of dyspnoea and noisy breathing. Her parents called an ambulance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes intermittent asthma. She is taking regular inhaled corticosteroids with poor adherence, as well as short-acting beta-agonists as needed. She has no known allergies and her immunisations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 124/min, blood pressure 76/55 mmHg, respiratory rate 30/min, and oxygen saturation 92% on room air. There is an audible wheeze and a persistent cough.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most crucial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Administer 8 mg dexamethasone PO","Administer 5 mg salbutamol via nebuliser","Administer 300 micrograms adrenaline IM","Administer 100% oxygen via face mask","Administer normal saline 20 mL/kg IV"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is presenting with signs and symptoms consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eanaphylaxis\u003C/strong\u003E, a severe and potentially life-threatening allergic reaction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnaphylaxis is a clinical diagnosis made after an acute onset of either:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETypical skin features i.e. urticaria, flushing, angioedema as well as an involvement of the respiratory system, and/or cardiovascular system, and/or persistent severe gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECardiovascular systems (Hypotension), respiratory symptoms ( bronchospasm or upper airway obstruction) where anaphylaxis is possible (even if typical skin features are not present).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the patient is lacking the typical skin features, however presents with hypotension (cardiovascular compromise) and dyspnoea (respiratory compromise) which meets the clinical diagnosis criteria for anaphylaxis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EIn a situation where the diagnosis of anaphylaxis or asthma is uncertain, anaphylaxis should be be assumed first, even if the treatment of both is time-critical.\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister 300 micrograms adrenaline IM\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first step in management. Intramuscular adrenaline is the first-line treatment for anaphylaxis. It works by causing vasoconstriction (thereby increasing blood pressure), bronchodilation, and stabilisation of mast cells and basophils, thus counteracting the pathophysiological processes of anaphylaxis. The dose of 300 micrograms (0.3 mg) is appropriate for a child weighing more than 30 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister 100% oxygen via face mask\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal saline 20 mL/kg IV\u003C/strong\u003E are important supportive measures in anaphylaxis, particularly given this patient\u0027s respiratory distress and hypotension. However, they should be implemented after the administration of adrenaline, which is the most critical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister 5 mg salbutamol via nebuliser\u003C/strong\u003E can help treat bronchospasm and wheeze associated with anaphylaxis. However, it does not treat the underlying allergic reaction and should not be prioritised over adrenaline.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister 8 mg dexamethasone PO\u003C/strong\u003E may be given to help prevent biphasic or protracted reactions in anaphylaxis. However, the onset of action of oral steroids is slow, and they play no role in the acute management of anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter administering adrenaline, the patient should be closely monitored with frequent reassessments. Repeat doses of adrenaline may be necessary if there is no improvement. The patient will require admission for observation even if they respond to initial treatment, as delayed reactions can occur.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaphylaxis is a severe and life-threatening allergic reaction that should be treated promptly with the administration of IM adrenaline.","In a situation where the diagnosis of anaphylaxis or asthma is uncertain, anaphylaxis should be prioritised, even if the treatment of both is time-critical."],"references":["Ring J, Beyer K, Biedermann T, Bircher A, Duda D, Fischer J, Friedrichs F, Fuchs T, Gieler U, Jakob T, Klimek L. Guideline for acute therapy and management of anaphylaxis. Allergo journal international. 2014 May;23(3):96-112.","Cardona V, Ansotegui IJ, Ebisawa M, El-Gamal Y, Rivas MF, Fineman S, Geller M, Gonzalez-Estrada A, Greenberger PA, Borges MS, Senna G. World allergy organization anaphylaxis guidance 2020. World allergy organization journal. 2020 Oct 1;13(10):100472.","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital Melbourne. Anaphylaxis. Available at: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/anaphylaxis/ (Accessed: 20 December 2024)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92235"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11692"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92235","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92235"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-27T12:12:01+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-27T12:13:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4307"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109866"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups